[[Image:Windflow's prototype windmill.jpg|thumb|160px|right|Windflow Technology's prototype windmill was named Neil to honour Cherry.]] '''Neil James Cherry''' {{post-nominals|country=NZL|ONZM|size=85%}} (29 September 1946 – 24 May 2003) was a [[New Zealand]] [[environmental science|environmental scientist]].
Cherry was born in [[Christchurch]] in 1946. His parents were James Conrad Cherry and Mona Hartley, who had married in 1940. Cherry could trace his ancestry back to the ''[[Cressy (ship)|Cressy]]'', one of the [[First Four Ships]] that started the settlement of [[Canterbury, New Zealand|Canterbury]].<ref name="Part 1">{{cite web |last1=Hunt |first1=Dorothy |title=Neil Cherry ONZM - his life and work: Part 1 |url=http://www.nzine.co.nz/features/neilcherry_lifestory_part1.html |publisher=NZine |accessdate=14 May 2017 |date=28 March 2003}}</ref>
Cherry specialised most recently in the effects of [[electromagnetic radiation]] on human health, following his earlier work in [[meteorology]] and [[wind energy]]. He was also a Councillor on the [[Canterbury Regional Council (Environment Canterbury)]], and was appointed an [[New Zealand Order of Merit|Officer of the New Zealand Order of Merit]] in the [[2002 New Year Honours]] for service to science, education and the community.{{Citation needed|date= January 2018}} He was diagnosed with [[motor neurone disease]] in 2001 and became increasingly immobile until his death in 2003.{{Citation needed|date= January 2018}}
